WEBVTT

00:11.834 --> 00:13.500
[static drones]

00:13.567 --> 00:16.333
[bright tone]

00:16.400 --> 00:19.333
[tense jazzy music]

00:19.400 --> 00:26.433
♪ ♪

01:46.433 --> 01:51.066
[tense percussive music]

01:51.133 --> 01:53.500
- 6% of the total
prison population

01:53.567 --> 01:55.567
is 55 and older.

01:55.633 --> 01:58.133
That's double
ten years ago.

01:58.200 --> 02:00.533
We say 55's old

02:00.600 --> 02:02.100
'cause criminal life
adds about

02:02.166 --> 02:04.200
ten years
worth of wrinkles.

02:04.266 --> 02:06.066
Still, in Oz,
you get decent food,

02:06.133 --> 02:08.266
exercise,
regular checkups.

02:08.333 --> 02:10.066
And if you
don't get whacked

02:10.133 --> 02:12.667
you live longer than you would
in your own hood.

02:12.734 --> 02:14.333
0 [grunting]

02:14.400 --> 02:15.500
[dramatic trumpet tones]

02:19.200 --> 02:20.967
Yeah,
the prison system.

02:21.033 --> 02:22.700
It can keep you alive,

02:22.767 --> 02:24.333
but it can't
take care of you.

02:24.400 --> 02:26.500
- I'm telling you,
we're ignoring the problem.

02:26.567 --> 02:28.600
We have to deal differently
with aging inmates.

02:28.667 --> 02:31.166
- That's right; Oz was designed
to punish the young.

02:31.233 --> 02:32.867
To keep 'em in line,
to keep 'em down.

02:32.934 --> 02:34.433
But with a guy
like Rebadow,

02:34.500 --> 02:36.200
we don't need
to keep him  down.

02:36.266 --> 02:37.600
- So what are you
proposing?

02:37.667 --> 02:39.467
- We turn Unit 2 into
a cellblock

02:39.533 --> 02:41.066
exclusively for seniors.

02:41.133 --> 02:42.533
They sleep together there,

02:42.600 --> 02:43.700
they can eat
all their meals together there,

02:43.767 --> 02:45.266
they can play cards,

02:45.333 --> 02:47.166
they want to watch
the TV shows they wanna watch.

02:47.233 --> 02:48.700
- On Saturday night,
bingo?

02:48.767 --> 02:50.166
- Why not?

02:50.233 --> 02:51.734
We need to
keep 'em active.

02:51.800 --> 02:54.333
- And less stress will help
slow down the aging process

02:54.400 --> 02:56.467
which will help save
on medical costs.

02:56.533 --> 02:58.467
- Plus, the older guys
are not a security problem.

02:58.533 --> 03:00.400
So you can save money
on the officers.

03:00.467 --> 03:03.066
- McManus, you've been
awfully quiet today.

03:03.133 --> 03:04.667
Never thought
I'd ask,

03:04.734 --> 03:06.867
but do you have
an opinion on this?

03:06.934 --> 03:08.133
- Sure.

03:08.200 --> 03:09.700
Sounds like a good idea.

03:10.800 --> 03:12.200
- That's it?

03:12.266 --> 03:13.967
- Yep.
- Hmm...

03:14.033 --> 03:15.633
Fine.

03:15.700 --> 03:17.367
I'll run it
by the commissioner.

03:18.767 --> 03:20.033
Meeting adjourned.

03:20.100 --> 03:21.367
- Finally.

03:21.433 --> 03:23.567
- [laughs]

03:25.767 --> 03:27.834
- Hey, Tim, you okay?

03:27.900 --> 03:30.367
You don't
look so good.

03:30.433 --> 03:31.400
You feeling all right?

03:31.467 --> 03:34.200
- I said yeah, okay?

03:34.266 --> 03:36.133
- Okay.

03:36.200 --> 03:37.500
Are you free
for dinner tonight?

03:37.567 --> 03:39.166
- "Dinner"?

03:39.233 --> 03:41.033
You think
I'm an asshole.

03:41.100 --> 03:43.200
- I do not  think--

03:43.266 --> 03:44.834
- Well, I appreciate
the offer.

03:44.900 --> 03:46.533
But the last thing
I need from you

03:46.600 --> 03:48.300
is a mercy dinner.

03:52.033 --> 03:54.033
- Bob Rebadow's
in the hospital, Kenny.

03:54.100 --> 03:55.200
- So?

03:55.266 --> 03:57.100
- So I'm pissed off
about that!

03:57.166 --> 03:58.333
- So?

03:58.400 --> 04:00.333
- So, I hear
you're responsible!

04:00.400 --> 04:01.867
- Where'd you hear
that from?

04:01.934 --> 04:03.567
- Oh, I got ears everywhere,
Kenny.

04:03.633 --> 04:04.734
I know it's true.

04:09.066 --> 04:11.400
You don't hit
old men, Kenny.

04:11.467 --> 04:12.800
You don't
hit old men--

04:12.867 --> 04:14.667
- What--what do you want,
McManus?

04:14.734 --> 04:16.834
- You see those guys
out there?

04:16.900 --> 04:19.667
If I tell 'em to, they will
gladly kick your ass!

04:19.734 --> 04:21.500
- So what?
I'm not afraid of them!

04:21.567 --> 04:22.934
- You're not?
- No!

04:23.000 --> 04:23.967
- Well, what are you
afraid of?!

04:24.033 --> 04:24.967
- I ain't afraid
of nothin'!

04:25.033 --> 04:26.133
- Nothing?
- Nothing!

04:26.200 --> 04:28.166
- You afraid of this?
Huh?

04:28.233 --> 04:30.000
You afraid of dying?

04:30.066 --> 04:32.600
You little fuckin'
punk ass!

04:32.667 --> 04:35.667
- [coughing]

04:38.066 --> 04:40.800
- Get him the
fuck outta here!

04:40.867 --> 04:44.433
- [gasping and panting]

04:47.834 --> 04:51.133
[dark music]

04:52.467 --> 04:55.400
- [exhaling]

05:00.266 --> 05:02.533
- Leo, what are you
doing here?

05:02.600 --> 05:05.133
- Same thing you are,
I guess.

05:05.200 --> 05:07.667
I like to work out when
no one else is around.

05:07.734 --> 05:10.500
- I'll ignore you
if you ignore me.

05:14.333 --> 05:15.834
- McManus...

05:15.900 --> 05:17.900
You okay?

05:17.967 --> 05:20.667
- Why does everybody
keep asking me that?

05:20.734 --> 05:22.300
- I don't know.

05:22.367 --> 05:24.367
Past few weeks
you seem different.

05:24.433 --> 05:26.100
- I'm fine.

05:27.800 --> 05:29.667
- Commissioner rejected
our proposal

05:29.734 --> 05:31.433
for a senior citizens unit.

05:31.500 --> 05:33.467
- Big surprise.

05:33.533 --> 05:35.266
Commissioner
didn't reject it,

05:35.333 --> 05:37.467
Governor Fuck-Wad did.

05:37.533 --> 05:40.033
- Well, Devlin's
almost out of office.

05:40.100 --> 05:42.500
He's on trial
for taking those kickbacks,

05:42.567 --> 05:45.600
for lying, fraud,

05:45.667 --> 05:46.900
extortion.

05:46.967 --> 05:48.500
- I'll miss him!

05:51.033 --> 05:53.567
- I've been
hearing rumors

05:53.633 --> 05:54.900
that you're living
in Emerald City.

05:54.967 --> 05:56.600
That you never
leave the grounds,

05:56.667 --> 05:58.467
you never
go home anymore.

05:58.533 --> 06:00.533
- Since when do you
listen to gossip?

06:00.600 --> 06:03.533
- I've been dancing down
these hallways a long time.

06:03.600 --> 06:05.767
I've seen this place
change people completely

06:05.834 --> 06:07.633
and not just
the prisoners.

06:07.700 --> 06:09.600
If you're
not careful, Tim,

06:09.667 --> 06:12.266
Oz will nick away
at your soul.

06:12.333 --> 06:14.300
- Huh.

06:14.367 --> 06:17.500
That's the first time
you ever called me "Tim."

06:20.233 --> 06:23.800
- You know, you don't even
have to be 55t o be old.

06:24.533 --> 06:28.333
[tense percussive tones]

06:31.934 --> 06:35.133
- Take a break.
- Okay, Mr. McManus.

06:52.734 --> 06:54.500
- How you feeling?

06:54.567 --> 06:57.667
- I can't stay here anymore.

06:57.734 --> 07:00.400
- In the hospital?
- In Oz.

07:00.467 --> 07:02.000
- Why?

07:02.066 --> 07:03.367
- I'm afraid.

07:03.433 --> 07:04.900
- Of what?

07:04.967 --> 07:06.667
- Them, the young.

07:06.734 --> 07:08.333
When I first
came to Oz

07:08.400 --> 07:10.066
we treated our elders
with dignity.

07:10.133 --> 07:12.400
But these kids,
it's all different now.

07:12.467 --> 07:15.100
I've decided to leave.

07:15.166 --> 07:16.767
- Leave?

07:16.834 --> 07:18.700
Escape.

07:20.533 --> 07:22.367
- How you gonna
do that?

07:22.433 --> 07:25.266
- God will show me the way.

07:26.667 --> 07:29.600
[tense percussive tones]

07:29.667 --> 07:36.700
♪ ♪

07:38.233 --> 07:42.333
[guards laughing]

07:42.400 --> 07:49.467
♪ ♪

07:59.033 --> 08:00.734
[gasps]

08:00.800 --> 08:03.000
[pounding on door]

08:03.066 --> 08:05.300
[panting]

08:05.367 --> 08:12.400
♪ ♪

08:14.967 --> 08:16.400
- The human body,

08:16.467 --> 08:18.467
it's amazing.

08:18.533 --> 08:20.834
Made up of all these...

08:20.900 --> 08:23.000
cells and neutrons

08:23.066 --> 08:25.433
and veins
and shit like that.

08:25.500 --> 08:27.100
So many little pieces,

08:27.166 --> 08:28.834
so many things
that can break down.

08:28.900 --> 08:31.333
Add to that the wear and tear
we give our bodies

08:31.400 --> 08:34.033
what with the drugs
and drinking

08:34.100 --> 08:35.967
and chicken fried steak.

08:36.033 --> 08:38.066
Man, that any of us
is still standing,

08:38.133 --> 08:39.700
still breathing.

08:39.767 --> 08:41.266
It's a miracle.

08:41.333 --> 08:43.567
- Breakfast time, boys!

08:43.633 --> 08:45.367
- Let's go, Alvarez.

08:45.433 --> 08:49.066
- [speaking gibberish]

08:49.133 --> 08:51.500
- I think maybe
we got a problem.

08:51.567 --> 08:53.800
- What?
- Look at Alvarez.

08:55.166 --> 08:57.033
- [mumbling]

09:03.200 --> 09:04.633
- Hey, Alvarez.

09:04.700 --> 09:06.567
- You think he's sleeping?

09:06.633 --> 09:08.667
- Alvarez?

09:08.734 --> 09:11.066
- [mumbling]
- Alvarez!

09:11.934 --> 09:13.333
Alvarez!

09:13.400 --> 09:15.633
- [mumbling]

09:15.700 --> 09:17.834
- Call for the doctor.

09:19.467 --> 09:23.867
- Prisoner number 43A515,
Ricardo Alvarez.

09:23.934 --> 09:26.967
Convicted March 3rd, '43,
armed robbery,

09:27.033 --> 09:29.200
sentence: 20 years.

09:29.266 --> 09:32.600
Convicted June 6th, '61,
murder in the first degree.

09:32.667 --> 09:36.633
Sentence: life imprisonment,
solitary confinement.

09:41.166 --> 09:43.700
- Ricardo, We're gonna start
with a series of tests.

09:43.767 --> 09:47.600
- [speaking Spanish]

09:47.667 --> 09:49.400
- You have to go home?

09:50.633 --> 09:52.567
- [speaking Spanish]

09:52.633 --> 09:54.266
- Your mother.

09:54.333 --> 09:57.033
Ricardo, where are you?
- [speaking Spanish]

09:57.100 --> 09:58.800
- Do you know what
city you're in?

09:58.867 --> 10:00.300
[speaks Spanish]

10:03.000 --> 10:05.767
- [speaks Spanish]

10:05.834 --> 10:07.200
- So, we're agreed?

10:07.266 --> 10:09.133
The medication's controlling
Cragen's paranoia?

10:09.200 --> 10:10.800
- Yeah, we should
keep him on it.

10:10.867 --> 10:12.200
- Definitely.

10:12.266 --> 10:14.900
- Thank you.
Next is Miguel Alvarez.

10:14.967 --> 10:16.667
- Oh, yeah, I'm scheduled

10:16.734 --> 10:20.100
to do a psychiatric
re-evaluation on Thursday.

10:20.166 --> 10:22.867
- Good luck, Pete, his baby died
right after birth.

10:22.934 --> 10:24.133
He's pretty depressed.

10:24.200 --> 10:26.000
- He's about to become
even more depressed.

10:26.066 --> 10:28.200
His grandfather Ricardo Alvarez,
has Alzheimer's.

10:28.266 --> 10:30.333
- Oh, boy,
does his family know?

10:30.400 --> 10:32.066
- No, not yet.

10:32.133 --> 10:34.467
Ricardo's son, Eduardo,
is an orderly in my ward.

10:34.533 --> 10:36.200
I'll tell him when
he comes in for his shift.

10:36.266 --> 10:38.900
- Eduardo, that's the one
with no tongue, right?

10:38.967 --> 10:40.633
- Uh-huh.
- I'll talk to Miguel.

10:40.700 --> 10:42.567
- Listen, Tim, could I do that?

10:42.633 --> 10:44.066
If you don't mind.

10:44.133 --> 10:46.433
- Hey, I'm always willing
to give up an opportunity

10:46.500 --> 10:48.400
to deliver bad news.

10:48.467 --> 10:49.734
Next.

10:50.667 --> 10:52.300
- Miguel, I need you
to come with me.

10:52.367 --> 10:54.633
- I didn't do shit.
- Miguel, please?

10:54.700 --> 10:56.333
Come on.

10:59.433 --> 11:00.834
- Maricón.

11:02.533 --> 11:05.567
- How come no one knew 'til now
that Ricardo's mind was going?

11:05.633 --> 11:07.266
- He's in solitary, Miguel.

11:07.333 --> 11:09.300
He hardly says
three words a day to anyone.

11:09.367 --> 11:13.133
- There's nothing we could've
done to stop the disease anyway.

11:13.200 --> 11:15.200
- So what happens now?

11:15.266 --> 11:17.500
- Well,
that's the tricky part.

11:17.567 --> 11:19.834
- Unfortunately Oz
is just not equipped

11:19.900 --> 11:21.633
for long-term
custodial care.

11:21.700 --> 11:23.834
And there isn't
anywhere else to send him.

11:23.900 --> 11:26.100
- You're telling me
the state doesn't have a place

11:26.166 --> 11:27.433
to take care of
its old prisoners?

11:27.500 --> 11:28.734
- The state?

11:28.800 --> 11:30.667
The state's attitude
toward the elderly,

11:30.734 --> 11:32.633
any  elderly,
in or out of prison,

11:32.700 --> 11:36.033
is hurry up and die.

11:38.734 --> 11:40.633
- I wanna see
my grandfather.

11:43.066 --> 11:46.100
[monitors beeping]

11:56.200 --> 11:57.600
- Hey.

11:57.667 --> 11:59.500
- Hey.

12:01.834 --> 12:03.934
- It's me, Miguel,
and Eduardo.

12:07.133 --> 12:08.467
- Hey!

12:08.533 --> 12:10.934
- Eduardo, your son.

12:11.000 --> 12:13.166
Miguel, grandson.

12:13.233 --> 12:14.467
- Hey!

12:15.867 --> 12:20.033
[whimpering]

12:20.100 --> 12:22.233
Hey, hey, hey...

12:22.300 --> 12:25.000
Hey, hey, hey.

12:25.066 --> 12:28.500
- You know what we should do
with Ricardo Alvarez?

12:28.567 --> 12:30.834
- What's that?

12:30.900 --> 12:32.967
- Let him go free.

12:36.400 --> 12:39.033
- Hey, hey, hey, hey...

12:39.100 --> 12:41.567
hey, hey, hey, hey.

12:41.633 --> 12:43.400
- "Let him go free"?

12:43.467 --> 12:45.000
The man is
a convicted killer.

12:45.066 --> 12:46.600
- He stabbed the inmate
who cut his son's tongue out.

12:46.667 --> 12:48.200
- And he's old.

12:48.266 --> 12:49.500
- He's old, Leo.

12:49.567 --> 12:51.333
- Old doesn't
necessarily mean nice.

12:51.400 --> 12:53.133
If you have any
doubts about that,

12:53.200 --> 12:55.266
spend ten minutes
with my mother-in-law.

12:55.333 --> 12:57.367
- Leo, a 31-year-old inmate

12:57.433 --> 12:59.600
costs $21,000 a year
to maintain.

12:59.667 --> 13:01.700
A senior costs
three times that amount.

13:01.767 --> 13:04.266
- Since when did you get
so interested in the budget?

13:04.333 --> 13:06.033
- Since I figured out that
the money we're gonna waste

13:06.100 --> 13:07.433
taking care of
Ricardo Alvarez

13:07.500 --> 13:08.800
could be put
to much better use.

13:08.867 --> 13:10.667
- Besides, Ricardo doesn't know
where he is

13:10.734 --> 13:12.266
or even why he's here!

13:12.333 --> 13:14.934
There is  such a thing
as criminal menopause, right?

13:15.000 --> 13:17.066
Look, he cannot commit
the crime again.

13:17.133 --> 13:18.934
The man is no longer
a threat to anybody.

13:19.000 --> 13:20.533
- Yeah, but it didn't
change what he did.

13:20.600 --> 13:22.066
And it doesn't
change his sentence.

13:22.133 --> 13:24.400
Life imprisonment
means just that.

13:24.467 --> 13:26.567
Besides, if he really
doesn't know he's in prison,

13:26.633 --> 13:29.166
then he's already free,
isn't he?

13:34.500 --> 13:35.800
- While I was growing up,

13:35.867 --> 13:39.266
both my father and
my grandfather came to Oz.

13:39.333 --> 13:42.133
You know, when I was little,
I always wondered

13:42.200 --> 13:43.900
what was so great
about prison

13:43.967 --> 13:46.367
that they'd wanna
leave us and come here.

13:47.900 --> 13:50.000
But you a kid,
you know,

13:50.066 --> 13:52.000
what do you know?

13:52.066 --> 13:53.867
- Yeah.

13:53.934 --> 13:56.767
So, the word
"grandfather,"

13:56.834 --> 13:58.467
what does the word

13:58.533 --> 14:01.333
mean to you,
emotionally?

14:01.400 --> 14:03.400
- Nothin'.

14:03.467 --> 14:05.800
Don't mean nothin'
at all to me.

14:05.867 --> 14:09.500
[chuckles]
"Pizza" means more.

14:09.567 --> 14:11.100
"Doorknob."

14:12.300 --> 14:14.333
- Would you like
"grandfather"

14:14.400 --> 14:16.066
to mean something
to you?

14:17.900 --> 14:19.033
- Yeah.

14:20.800 --> 14:23.266
- Dr. Nathan's
not sure how long

14:23.333 --> 14:25.266
your grandfather
has to live.

14:26.400 --> 14:27.834
Look.

14:27.900 --> 14:30.900
Since your father's an orderly
in the prison hospital

14:30.967 --> 14:33.000
and is gonna spend the remaining
time with your grandfather,

14:33.066 --> 14:35.100
there's no reason you can't
do the same thing.

14:35.166 --> 14:37.533
Maybe if you
take care of him

14:37.600 --> 14:39.934
you'll learn
to care for him.

14:44.066 --> 14:45.934
- You know,
in my family,

14:46.000 --> 14:48.233
Ricardo was like a god.

14:48.300 --> 14:50.300
You know, he was a legend.

14:50.367 --> 14:52.800
My grandmother used to
show me these pictures.

14:52.867 --> 14:55.266
You know, tell me stories
all about him.

14:56.600 --> 14:58.967
And I wanted--I wanted
to be like him.

14:59.033 --> 15:01.233
You know?
- Yeah.

15:04.200 --> 15:07.433
- And now I see
he's just a man.

15:07.500 --> 15:09.800
You know, he's just an old man

15:09.867 --> 15:12.934
and he's rottin' away.

15:13.000 --> 15:16.100
I don't wanna end up
like my grandfather.

15:16.166 --> 15:18.033
- You don't have to, Miguel.

15:18.100 --> 15:19.967
- Oh, really?

15:20.033 --> 15:23.433
Well, I don't see it
going down any other way.

15:34.266 --> 15:35.900
- Rebadow.

15:38.033 --> 15:40.200
I'm sorry you didn't
make it out.

15:40.266 --> 15:42.367
- It's okay.
It was worth it.

15:45.633 --> 15:46.867
The adrenaline rush,

15:46.934 --> 15:49.467
I felt 25 again
for a moment.

15:51.300 --> 15:54.367
- Here's your dinner.
- I don't want it.

15:54.433 --> 15:57.934
- Okay.
What do you want?

15:58.000 --> 16:01.166
- I'd like a few years
at the end of my life

16:01.233 --> 16:03.200
to be free.

16:11.166 --> 16:12.900
- Do we care for people
when they're sick

16:12.967 --> 16:15.567
'cause we actually
care about them?

16:15.633 --> 16:18.400
- [mumbles] Guys...

16:18.467 --> 16:21.600
- Or do we care for them
because when our time comes

16:21.667 --> 16:23.233
we want someone
to care for us?

16:26.066 --> 16:28.100
Or does it matter?

16:30.734 --> 16:32.700
At least you got
your health!

16:32.767 --> 16:35.066
Don't you hate it
when people say that?!

16:35.133 --> 16:37.700
I mean, you lose your job,
you lose your wife,

16:37.767 --> 16:39.266
you're in prison

16:39.333 --> 16:40.767
and some punk-ass
do-gooder says,

16:40.834 --> 16:42.233
"At least you got
your health!"

16:42.300 --> 16:44.300
Like that's supposed
to make you feel better!

16:44.367 --> 16:45.633
So what if I'm broke?

16:45.700 --> 16:47.533
So what if some dealer
wants to cap my ass?

16:47.600 --> 16:49.200
At least I ain't
got a tumor!

16:49.266 --> 16:52.667
I swear the next person that
says "A.L.Y.G.Y.H." to me,

16:52.734 --> 16:56.166
I'ma make sure they ain't got
